# Code Conventions

## Overview

This document describes the coding conventions for [Project Name]. Follow these guidelines to maintain consistency across the codebase.

## General Principles

1. **Readability over cleverness** - Code is read more than written
2. **Explicit over implicit** - Be clear about intent
3. **Consistency** - Follow existing patterns in the codebase
4. **Simplicity** - Don't over-engineer

## Naming Conventions

### Files and Directories
```
# Components (PascalCase)
UserProfile.tsx
AuthService.ts

# Utilities (camelCase)
formatDate.ts
apiHelpers.ts

# Constants (SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE in code, kebab-case for files)
constants.ts → export const MAX_RETRIES = 3

# Tests (same name with .test or .spec suffix)
UserProfile.test.tsx
formatDate.spec.ts
```

### Variables and Functions
```typescript
// Variables: camelCase
const userName = 'John';
const isActive = true;
const itemCount = 42;

// Functions: camelCase, verb prefix
function getUserById(id: string) {}
function calculateTotal(items: Item[]) {}
function isValidEmail(email: string) {}

// Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE
const MAX_ITEMS = 100;
const API_BASE_URL = 'https://api.example.com';

// Private: underscore prefix (if needed)
private _internalState = {};
```

### Types and Interfaces
```typescript
// Types and Interfaces: PascalCase
interface UserProfile {
  id: string;
  name: string;
}

type ButtonVariant = 'primary' | 'secondary';

// Enums: PascalCase with PascalCase members
enum UserRole {
  Admin = 'admin',
  User = 'user',
  Guest = 'guest',
}
```

## Code Formatting

### Indentation
- Use [2/4] spaces (no tabs)
- Configure editor to convert tabs to spaces

### Line Length
- Maximum 100 characters per line
- Break long lines at logical points

### Braces
```typescript
// Same-line opening brace
if (condition) {
  // code
}

// Functions
function doSomething() {
  // code
}

// Classes
class MyClass {
  // code
}
```

### Imports
```typescript
// Order: external packages, then internal modules, then relative imports
// Separate groups with blank lines

import React from 'react';
import { useState } from 'react';

import { apiClient } from '@/services/api';
import { formatDate } from '@/utils/date';

import { Button } from './Button';
import styles from './styles.module.css';
```

## TypeScript Conventions

### Type Annotations
```typescript
// Always annotate function parameters and returns
function greet(name: string): string {
  return `Hello, ${name}`;
}

// Use interfaces for objects
interface Config {
  apiUrl: string;
  timeout: number;
}

// Use type for unions and primitives
type Status = 'pending' | 'active' | 'completed';
```

### Avoid `any`
```typescript
// Bad
function process(data: any) {}

// Good
function process(data: unknown) {}
function process<T>(data: T) {}
```

## Error Handling

```typescript
// Use try-catch for async operations
async function fetchUser(id: string): Promise<User> {
  try {
    const response = await api.get(`/users/${id}`);
    return response.data;
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof NotFoundError) {
      throw new UserNotFoundError(id);
    }
    throw error;
  }
}

// Use Result types for expected failures
type Result<T, E> = { ok: true; value: T } | { ok: false; error: E };
```

## Comments

```typescript
// Single line comments for brief explanations
const timeout = 5000; // milliseconds

/**
 * Multi-line comments for complex logic.
 * Explain WHY, not WHAT (code explains what).
 */
function complexAlgorithm() {
  // ...
}

// TODO: Brief description of what needs to be done
// FIXME: Description of bug that needs fixing
// HACK: Explanation of why this workaround exists
```

## Git Conventions

### Commit Messages
```
type(scope): brief description

[optional body with more details]

[optional footer with references]
```

**Types:**
- `feat`: New feature
- `fix`: Bug fix
- `docs`: Documentation
- `style`: Formatting (no code change)
- `refactor`: Code restructuring
- `test`: Adding tests
- `chore`: Maintenance

**Examples:**
```
feat(auth): add password reset functionality

fix(api): handle timeout errors gracefully

docs(readme): update installation instructions
```

### Branch Naming
```
feature/short-description
bugfix/issue-description
hotfix/critical-fix
```

## File Organization

```typescript
// Component file structure
// 1. Imports
// 2. Types/Interfaces
// 3. Constants
// 4. Helper functions
// 5. Component definition
// 6. Exports

import React from 'react';
import styles from './styles.module.css';

interface Props {
  title: string;
}

const DEFAULT_TITLE = 'Untitled';

function formatTitle(title: string): string {
  return title.toUpperCase();
}

export function MyComponent({ title }: Props) {
  return <h1>{formatTitle(title)}</h1>;
}
```

## Testing Conventions

```typescript
// Test file naming
ComponentName.test.tsx
functionName.spec.ts

// Test structure (Arrange, Act, Assert)
describe('ComponentName', () => {
  it('should render correctly', () => {
    // Arrange
    const props = { title: 'Test' };

    // Act
    render(<Component {...props} />);

    // Assert
    expect(screen.getByText('Test')).toBeInTheDocument();
  });
});
```

## DO and DON'T

### DO
- Write self-documenting code
- Keep functions small and focused
- Handle errors explicitly
- Write tests for new features
- Review your own code before PR

### DON'T
- Don't leave commented-out code
- Don't use magic numbers (use named constants)
- Don't ignore linter warnings
- Don't commit console.log statements
- Don't merge without tests passing

